Moose Landcape Change Hypothesis Analysis

Tyler Muhly

12/12/2019

Introduction

Here I summarize data to explore the moose ‘landscape change hypothesis’ (LCH). The moose LCH posits that recent moose population declines in parts of central British Columbia (BC) were related to large-scale changes to forest cover (i.e., landscape disturbance), caused by an extensive mountain pine beetle (MBP) infestation and subsequent forest harvest to salvage MPB killed forest stands. As a preliminary test of the LCH, I relate estimates of forest disturbance from MPB and forestry (cutblocks) to estimates of adult female moose survival and cow/calf moose ratios measured in five study areas.

The LCH predicts a negative correlative relationship between the amount of landscape disturbance and adult female survival or the ratio of calves to cow moose. This relationship is indicative that processes related to landscape disturbance, i.e., reduced amount of security and thermal cover and increased amount of negative interactions with humans (e.g., hunting mortality) due to higher road densities are causing moose population declines.

Methods

Study Areas

The LCH was tested by sampling moose survival rates in the Big Creek, Bonaparte, Entiako, John Prince Research Forest (JPRF) and Prince George South study areas. These five study areas were selected because they had varied levels of MPB and forestry disturbance. A sample of moose in each study area were captured annually and collared with global positioning system (GPS) telemetry collars. Annual moose study area boundaries were determined by calculating the 100% minimum convex polygon (MCP) of annual sampled adult female moose GPS locations in each area. Moose locations were collected for four years from 2015 to 2018 (except Entiako, where data was also collected in 2014), and thus study area boundaries were re-calculated for each of these years.

Population Data

Adult female moose survival rates were estimated annually from mortality data collected from the sampled animals. Survival was estimated for a biological year, i.e., April to April(?), not a calendar year. Thus, for example, a survival estimate for 2015 was caculated using mortality data collected from April 2014 to April 2015. In addition, aerial cow/calf composition surveys were completed annually in each study area in ????.

Estimating Area of Cutblocks in Study Areas

I estimated the area of less than 8 and less than 15 year old forestry cutblocks and MPB disturbed stands in each study area. I estimated the area of cutblocks using the consolidated cutblocks dataset for BC. I intersected this data with the study area boundaries and then summarized the area cut by year from 1970 to 2018. I then calculated the area of cutblocks less than 8 and 15 years old for each study area year to align with adult female moose survival estimates for that year. For example, for survival estimates calculated for year 2015, I calculated the area cut from 2008 to 2015 as an estimate of area cut less than 8 years old. Thus, the assumption was the majority of area was cut early in a calendar year, during the period which survival estimates were calculated.

Estimating Area of Mountain Pine Beetle Disturbed Stands in Study Areas

I estimated the area of forest stands disturbed by mountain pine beetle in each study area using data collected from annual aerial surveys by the government of BC. These data were accessible through an FTP site, and I downloaded annual datasets from 1999 to 2018. I summarized the area of moderately (11 to 29%), severely (30 to 49%) and very severely (>50%) disturbed forest stands for each year. Estimates cannot be added cumulatively each year, as damage to stands measured in previous years may be updated with new data from subsequent years. Thus I ensured that spatially overlapping stands were updated using ArcGIS. I then calculated the area of MPB disturbed stands less than 8 and less than 15 years old for each study area year to align with adult female moose survival estimates for that year. MPB surveys were typically completed in July-August, thus, for example, for survival estimates calculated for year 2015, I calculated the area of MPB disturbed stands from 2008 to 2015 as an estimate of area of MPB stands less than 8 years old.

Preliminary Results

Here I provide a preliminary description of the relationship between landscape disturbance and estimates of moose adult female survival or calves/100 cows. Entiako was typically the largest study area, at approximately 1,000,000 ha, and Bonaparte was typically the smallest study area, at approximately 300,000 ha (Table 2). The JPRF study area had typically the highest amount of less than 8 year old cutblocks, and Prince George South had the highest amount of less than 15 year old cutblocks. The Big Creek study area typically had the most less than 8 year old MPB disturbed forest stands and Prince George South had the highest amount of less than 15 year MPB disturbed forest stands.

Trends in adult female moose survival rates varied across the study areas from 2015 to 2018 (Fig. 1). Survival was increasing in the Bonaparte, Entiako adn JPRF study areas, and decreasing in the Big Creek and Prince George South study areas.

Trends in calf/100 cow ratios varied across the study areas from 2015 to 2018 (Fig. 2). Calf/100 cow ratios were increasing in the Bonaparte study area, decreasing in the Entiako, JPRF and Prince Goerge SOtuh study areas, and flat in the Big Creek study area.

Relationship Between Cutblocks and Adult Female Survival

There was no clear relationship between the amount of less than 8 year old cutblocks and adult female moose survival rates across the five study areas (Fig. 3). There was a negative relationship in the Entiako and JPRF study areas, a positive relationship in the Big Creek and Prince George South study areas and no relationship in the Bonaparte study area.

Similarly, there was no clear relationship between the percent area less than 8 year old cutblocks and adult female moose survival rates across the five study areas (Fig. 4). There was a negative relationship in the Bonaparte and Entiako study areas, and a positive relationship in the Big Creek, JPRF and Prince George South study areas.

When considering the relationship between annual change in 8 year old cutblocks and annual change in adult female moose survival rates, there was no clear relationship across the five study areas (Fig. 5). There was a negative relationship in the Bonaparte and Entiako study areas, and a positive relationship in the Big Creek, JPRF and Prince George South study areas.

There was no clear relationship between the area of less than 15 year old cutblocks and adult female moose survival rates across the five study areas (Fig. 6). There was a negative relationship in the JPRF study area, a positive relationship in the Bonaparte and Entiako study areas and no relationship in the Big Creek and Prince George South study areas.

There was generally a positive relationship between the percent area less than 15 year old cutblocks and adult female moose survival rates across the five study areas (Fig. 7). This did not support the hypothesis that more forestry disturbance increased mrotality risk for moose.

There was also generally a positive relationship between the rate of change in area of cutblocks less than 15 years old and change in adult female moose survival rates across the five study areas (Fig. 8). This did not support the hypothesis that more forestry disturbance increased mrotality risk for moose.

Relationship Between Cutblocks and Calf/Cow Ratios

There was no clear relationship between the area of less than 8 year old cutblocks and calf/cow ratios across the five study areas (Fig. 9). There was a positive relationship in the Entiako and JPRF study areas and no relationship in the Big Creek, Bonaparte and Prince George South study areas.

Similarly, there was no clear relationship between the change in percent area of less than 8 year old cutblocks and change in calf/cow ratios across the five study areas (Fig. 10). There was a positive relationship in the Big Creek, Entiako and Prince George South study areas and no relationship in the Bonaparte and JPRF study areas.

There was no clear relationship between the area of less than 15 year old cutblocks and calf/cow ratios across the five study areas (Fig. 11). There was a negative relationship in the Big Creek, Entiako and Prince George South study areas and a positive relationship in the Bonaparte and JPRF study areas.

Similarly, there was no clear relationship between the change in percent area of less than 15 year old cutblocks and change in calf/cow ratios across the five study areas (Fig. 12). There was a negative relationship in the JPRF study area, a positive relationship in the Bonaparte and Prince George South study areas and no relationsip in the Big Creek and Entiako study areas.

In general, there was no clear relationship between forest cutblock disturbance and moose population parameters in the five study areas over time. If anything, these preliminary results indicate an overall positive relationship between forestry cutblocks and moose survival, although this realtionship was not clear enough across parameters and study areas.

Relationship Between Mountain Pine Beetle Disturbance and Adult Female Survival

There was no clear relationship between the area of less than 8 year old MPB disturbed stands and adult female moose survival rates across the five study areas (Fig. 13). There was a positive relationship in the Entiako and JPRF study areas and no relationship in the Big Creek, Bonaparte and Prince George South study areas.

Similarly, there was no clear relationship between the percent area of less than 8 year old MPB disturbed stands and adult female moose survival rates across the five study areas (Fig. 14). There was a negative relationship in the Entiako and JPRF study areas, and no relationship in the Big Creek, Bonaparte and Prince George South study areas.

There was no clear relationship between the change in percent area of less than 8 year old MPB disturbed stands and change in adult female moose survival rates across the five study areas (Fig. 15). There was a positive relationship in the Bonaparte study area, a negative relationship in Big Creek, Entiako and JPRF study areas and no relationship in the Prince George South study area.

There was generally a consistent, but weak negative relationship between the area of less than 15 year old MPB disturbed stands and adult female moose survival rates across the five study areas (Fig. 16). Adult female moose survival rates were lower in most study areas during periods when there was more area of less than 15 year old MPB disturbed stands. However, this relationship was not clear in the Prince George South study area.

There was no clear relationship between the percent area of less than 15 year old MPB disturbed stands and change in adult female moose survival rates across the five study areas (Fig. 17). There was a negative relationship in the Bonaparte and JPRF study areas and no relationship in the other study areas.

There was a consistent negative relationship between the change in percent area of less than 15 year old MPB disturbed stands and change in adult female moose survival rates across the five study areas (Fig. 18). As the area of less than 15 year old MPB disturbed stands increased, survival rate decreased.

Relationship Between Mountain Pine Beetle Disturbance and Calf/Cow Ratios

There was no clear relationship between the area of less than 8 year old MPB disturbed stands and the ratio of calves/100 cows across the five study areas (Fig. 19). There was a positive relationship in the Big Creek, Entiako and Prince George South study areas, a negative relationship in the JPRF study area and no relationship in the Bonaparte study area.

Similarly, there was no clear relationship between the percent area of less than 15 year old MPB disturbed stands and adult calf/cow ratios across the five study areas (Fig. 20). There was a negative relationship in the Big Creek and Prince George South study areas, positive in the JPRF study area and no relationship in the Bonaparte and Entiako study areas.

There was no clear relationship between the change in area of less than 8 year old MPB disturbed stands and the change in the ratio of calves/100 cows across the five study areas (Fig. 21). There was a positive relationship in the Big Creek, Entiako and Prince George South study areas, a negative relationship in the JPRF study area and no relationship in the Bonaparte study area.

Finally, there was no clear relationship between the change in area of less than 15 year old MPB disturbed stands and the change in the ratio of calves/100 cows across the five study areas (Fig. 22). There was a positive relationship in the Big Creek and Bonaparte study areas, a negative relationship in the Prince George South study area and no relationship in the Entiako and JPRF study areas.

Cumulative Disturbance

I considered the relationship between adult female moose survival rate and MPB disturbed stands plus cutblocks (i.e., cumulative disturbance). Note that care should be taken in interpreting these cumulative disturbance results, as they don’t account for spatial overlap of disturabnce types, and thus ‘double-count’ disturbances where they overlap. Nevertheless, here they likely provide some indication of whether both disturbance types together might be related to moose populaiton parameter estimates.

I found no clear relationship between adult female moose survival rate and cumulative disturbance less than 8 (Fig. 23) or 15 (Fig. 24) years old.

I also found no clear relationship between change in adult female moose survival rate and change cumulative disturbance less than 8 (Fig. 25) or 15 (Fig. 26) years old.

I considered the relationship between cow/calf ratios and MPB disturbed stands plus cutblocks (i.e., cumulative disturbance). I found no clear relationship between adult female moose survival rate and cumulative disturbance less than 8 (Fig. 27) or 15 (Fig. 28) years old.

I also found no clear relationship between change in adult female moose survival rate and change cumulative disturbance less than 8 (Fig. 29) or 15 (Fig. 30) years old.

Preliminary Conclusions

Across the five study areas. there was no clear relationship between landscape disturbance, here defined as cutblocks and MBP distrubed stands, and moose population parameters, i.e., adult female survival and calves/100 cows delta area lt 8 years old x delta survival rate ratio. The exception may have been the relationship beetween less than 15 year old MPB disturbed stands and change in adult female survival rate (Fig. 16), as this was consistently negative across the five study areas. However, this may have just been a stastical fluke, as I examined the data in a multitude of ways, and there was a likelihood that at least one of these ways would show the realtionship I was looking for.

Using the population parameter data here I cannot reject the null hypothesis of the LCH. However, this does not mean the LCH is not valid, but it is clearly diffcult to test at a ‘study area scale’ with only five study areas (i.e., n = 5) over a four year period. This justifies the need to implement long-term (i.e., multi-decade) monitoring programs to evaluate the effects of landscape change on wildlife.
